thread.title: $A falls on China economy worries

title: $A falls on China economy worries
text:
Tue, Sep 29, 2015, 5:31 PM AEST - Australia Markets closed $A falls on China economy worries AAP â€“ 17 minutes ago Print 
The Australian dollar has fallen well below 70 US cents as weak economic data from China dents confidence and weighs on commodity prices. 
At 1700 AEST on Tuesday, the local unit was trading at 69.47 US cents, down from 70.33 cents on Monday. 
It hit a low of 69.37 US cents during the day, its lowest level in almost four weeks, and nearing fresh six-and-a-half year lows. 
Profits from China's industrial sector fell 8.8 per cent in August, weighed down by August's currency devaluation, weak demand and plunging share prices. 
BK Asset Management managing director Kathy Lien said the data dented commodity currencies like the Australian dollar. 
"Earnings in the resource sector have been hit particularly hard and this put additional pressure on commodity prices," she said. 
IG chief market strategist Chris Weston said the Australian dollar could fall further on the growing concerns about China's economy, though steady iron ore prices are providing some support. 
"Some modest buying is creeping in, helped to a degree by some stability in iron ore futures," he said. 
CURRENCY SNAPSHOT AT 1700 AEST ON TUESDAY 
One Australian dollar buys: 
* 69.47 US cents, from 70.33 cents on Monday 
* 83.03 Japanese yen, from 84.72 yen 
* 61.68 euro cents, from 62.89 euro cents 
* 110.19 New Zealand cents, from 110.43 NZ cents 
* 45.82 British pence, from 46.31 pence 
(*Currency closes taken at 1700 AEST previous local session) 
Source: IRESS
